In this first step, the document was loaded from a plain text file into Python memory. The purpose of this stage is to verify that the 
source document can be accessed correctly and that its textual content is readable and complete. 

Creating a separate utils.py file improves the organization and scalability of the project by isolating reusable helper functions from
the main execution flow.
The chunk_text function splits the document into smaller overlapping chunks of 800 characters, with a 150-character overlap between
consecutive chunks. This size was chosen to keep enough context for meaningful retrieval while remaining small enough to search efficiently,
and the overlap helps preserve information that may fall across chunk boundaries.

This first function created, as an experiment, takes the user’s question and compares its words with the words in each chunk.
It assigns a score based on how many words overlap and returns the top three most relevant chunks. Although simple, this method helps 
illustrate how retrieval works before introducing more advanced techniques like embeddings.
At this stage, retrieval is based only on direct word overlap between the user’s question and each chunk.

The updated version of the retrieval function keeps the same word-overlap scoring approach, but first removes common stop words from both
the user’s question and the document chunks.

Next step is cleaning punctuation so matching becomes less noisy.
Right now:
	•	poison
	•	poison?
	•	poison,

are treated as different words, which is bad for retrieval.

The retrieval function was then updated to use a separate preprocessing helper, which cleaned punctuation, standardized capitalization
and removed stop words before computing word overlap scores

After retrieval, the top-ranked chunks were combined into a single context string to consolidate the most relevant information. This context serves
as the input that will later be provided to the language model.

The context is built.
Now the next step is to build the full prompt that we will later send to the LLM.

That prompt should include:
	•	an instruction
	•	the retrieved context
	•	the user’s question

A separate prompt.py module was created to isolate prompt design from the main pipeline logic and make the system easier to maintain and modify. 
Inside this module, a build_prompt function formats the prompt template with the retrieved context and the user’s question, and this function is 
then imported into main.py to generate the final prompt sent to the language model.

The retrieve_chunks function was improved by skipping chunks with a score of zero, so only relevant chunks are used even when selecting the 
top results.

Ollama was used to run a local open-source language model, allowing the generation step of the RAG pipeline to be completed without relying on
paid API access.


The retrieval function was replaced with a TF-IDF–based approach to improve the quality of chunk matching. Instead of counting simple word
overlap, both the query and document chunks are transformed into TF-IDF vectors, and cosine similarity is used to rank chunks based on the
importance of shared terms, resulting in more meaningful and relevant retrieval.

Now with the new tf-idf approach we do not need stop words and clean_words() function anymore.

The chunking function was updated to group complete sentences into chunks, ensuring that text is not split mid-sentence and preserving semantic
coherence for better retrieval.

The prompt was designed to enforce a structured output format, requiring the model to provide both a direct answer and a supporting sentence from the
context, ensuring that responses remain grounded in the retrieved information.

The final step of the pipeline consists of sending the constructed prompt to the imported Ollama model, which generates an answer based on
the retrieved context.